	<h2>The Trader Joe's Dynamic</h2>
	<p>Trader Joe's provides the highest quality-to-price ratio for groceries in Manhattan. Consequently, the stores operate at maximum capacity. The line frequently wraps around the interior perimeter of the store and sometimes extends onto the sidewalk.</p>
	
	<h3>Line Strategy</h3>
	<p>Do not wait until you have finished shopping to join the line. The established protocol is to join the checkout line immediately upon entering and select your items from the shelves as the line slowly moves past them. Shop during off-peak hours (Tuesday mornings or 9:00 PM on weekdays) to avoid systemic delays.</p>

	<h2>Alternative Sourcing</h2>
	<p>Relying on a single vendor limits operational flexibility.</p>
	
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Chinatown Produce Markets:</strong> The fruit and vegetable stands along Canal Street and Mott Street offer produce at prices 50% to 70% lower than traditional supermarkets. Quality is high, but shelf life is short. Consume these items quickly. Cash is required.</li>
		<li><strong>Target:</strong> Smaller format Target stores operate in Herald Square, the East Village, and Kips Bay. They provide reliable pricing on dry goods and toiletries.</li>
		<li><strong>Wegmans:</strong> The Astor Place location provides premium prepared foods and an expansive selection. Prices are higher than Trader Joe's but lower than Whole Foods. It serves as a strong alternative for specialty items.</li>
	</ul>
</InternWiki>
